either static tremor, rigidity, or both. However, the clini-
cal manifestations are various, including many non-motor 
symptoms [9]. Even with the use of strict clinical diagnostic 
criteria, the diagnostic error rate of PD ranges from 15 to 
24% in routine clinical practice [10, 11]. Future diagnostic 
algorithms of PD will need to incorporate additional tests 
and biomarkers to further enhance diagnostic accuracy and 
sensitivity for early disease stages.
Numerous researches have been invested in finding pro-
gression markers of PD. Biomarkers in cerebrospinal fluid 
(α-synuclein, tryptic peptide) of patients with PD had good 
diagnostic accuracy [12, 13]. However, this invasive detection 
method is not easily accepted by patients. Screening of PD mark-
ers in peripheral venous blood and sebum is a research hotspot 
in recent years. Plenty of published papers have focused on the 
change of metabolites in patients with PD plasma before. Poten-
tial markers involved in these studies include proteins, lipids, 
organic acids, and carbohydrate. Leng B et al. found that plasma 
levels of neuron-derived exosomal EAAT-2 and VGLUT-1 were 
significantly lower in PD patients than in healthy controls [14]. 
Alterations in the levels of serum sphingolipids and phospholip-
ids have been reported in PD [15–17]. There was an increase in 
the levels of phosphatidylcholine, with a simultaneous decrease 
in lyso-phosphatidylcholine, in the PD patients vs controls, sug-
gesting a potential role of these lipids as biomarkers [16]. Sper-
mine synthesis and N1,N8-diacetylspermidine may respectively 
be useful diagnostic and severity-associated biomarkers for PD 
[18]; Chang, K. H et al. found that the level of plasma ornithine 
could act as a biomarker of PD [19]. It has also been found 
that the fasting plasma insulin level in PD patients decreased 
significantly, and the fasting plasma islet amyloid polypeptide 
increased in older patients, and the stronger the insulin resist-
ance, the more obvious the non-motor disorder [20]. From 
the existing research, researchers have their own emphasis on 
analysis, and few studies have paid attention to the changes of 
screened analytes in the early and late stages of PD or in medi-
cated PD and drug naïve PD. Therefore, systematic analysis of 
plasma metabolites in patients with Parkinson’s disease is still 
scarce. Our previous research used ultra-high-pressure liquid 
chromatography tandem mass spectrometry (UPLC-MS) to 
profile 158 fatty acids and their metabolites in PD plasma. The 
results discovered that the fatty acid metabolites were helpful 
to diagnose PD [21]. In order to obtain more comprehensive 
plasma metabolic profiling of PD, a non-targeted way to analyze 
the plasma of PD was used by GC–MS.
Materials and Methods
Study Population
All the subjects were recruited from the Affiliated Hospital 
of Guangdong Medical University. This study was approved 
by the Institutional Review Committee of the Affiliated Hos-
pital of Guangdong Medical University. The inclusion cri-
teria of PD included (1) voluntarily agreed to participate in 
this study; (2) Parkinson's disease was diagnosed according 
to the UK PD Society Brain Bank clinical diagnostic cri-
teria; (3) no use of antibiotics for 3 months; (4) no use of 
immune-related drugs such as steroids for 3 months; (5) no 
use of lipid-lowering drugs for 1 month. Exclusion criteria 
of PD included (1) secondary Parkinson’s disease, atypical 
Parkinson’s disease, Alzheimer’s disease, or other central 
nervous system diseases; (2) abdominal cavity diseases; 
(3) a history of cancer surgery or medical treatment in the 
last 3 years; (4) pregnancy; (5) illiteracy; (6) the researcher 
judges that the candidate is not suitable to participate in 
this study. Neurologists will rule out some other diseases 
similar to Parkinson’s symptoms such as multiple system 
atrophy or essential tremor by their own clinical experience 
and Hoehn-Yahr stage was recorded for each PD patient. 
Sixty healthy individuals as the control group were recruited 
from the physical examination center of Guangdong Medical 
University Affiliated Hospital. The inclusion criteria are as 
follows: (1) voluntarily agreed to participate in this study; 
(2) be in good health and have no major diseases or organ 
diseases; (3) no pregnancy.
Demographic data and clinical biochemical indexes of the 
collected samples are shown in Table 1. Compared with the 
health, PD patients are older and have lower levels of total 
cholesterol and high density lipoprotein. Taking propionic 
acid as an example, we have constructed a linear regres-
sion model between age and propionic acid, in which R2 
is 0.222, and the correlation is weak (the closer r square is 
to 1, the higher the correlation is). Similarly, we also made 
linear regression analysis of HDL and propionic acid, and 
the results showed that R2 was 0.071, and the correlation 
is weak. We believe that the differences of these clinical 
indexes will not affect our analysis results. Of the 62 PD 
patients, 65% were medicated PD and 35% were drug naïve 
PD. Fifty-one cases were in the early stage of PD (ESPD) 
and 11 cases were in the advanced stage of PD (APSD).
Standard Solution and Quality Control Sample 
Preparation
In this study, heptadecanoic acid diluted with ethyl acetate 
to a final concentration of 100 μg/mL was used as the inter-
nal standard solution. Acetic acid and propanoic acid were 
diluted with pyridine to a final concentration of 100 μg/mL 
as external standard control.
The quality control sample (QC) was obtained by mixing 
the plasma of PD and health in equal proportion, which was 
used to check the analytical reproducibility and stability of 
instrument. QC was injected at the beginning of each analyt-
ical batch (n = 10), every 10th is injected, followed by a QC.
2620
Molecular Neurobiology (2023) 60:2619–2631
1 3
Biospecimen Collection and Processing
Fasting venous blood samples were collected into BD Vacu-
tainer ™ K2-EDTA tubes. Subsequently, plasma samples 
were transferred into sterile tubes after centrifugation at 
3000 rpm for 10 min and stored at − 80 °C.
Firstly, took 20 μL plasma and 15 μL internal standard 
solution in 1 mL methanol, and the mixture was vortexed at 
4℃ for 10 min, then centrifuged at 15,000 rpm for 5 min, and 
the supernatant was extracted into a glass bottle. Dried the 
supernatant with nitrogen. Dissolved the residue in the bottle 
with 50μL of 2% methoxyamine hydrochloride and react at 
37℃ for 90 min, then add 50μL of N, O-bis (trimethylsilyl) 
trifluoroacetamide (1% trimethylchlorosilane) into the bottle 
and react at 70℃ for 60 min. Samples were stored at − 80℃ 
before analysis to prevent metabolite degradation.
GC–MS Analysis
The plasma metabolites were analyzed by GCMS-QP2010 
(Shimadzu, Japan), and compounds in samples were sepa-
rated using a fused silica, nonpolar, capillary column DB-5 
30 m × 0.25 mm × 0.25 μm (Agilent, USA). The mass spec-
trometer was operated in the electron impact mode at 70 eV. 
The injection volume was 1 μL per sample and the split 
mode was set to splitless. The temperature program was as 
follows: the inlet temperature was set at 230 °C. The initial 
temperature was held at 85 °C for 2 min, elevated to 150 °C 
at a rate of 5 °C/min, increased to 240 °C at a rate of 15 °C/
min, raised to 280 °C by 40 °C/min, and then kept at 280 °C 
for 5 min. The temperature of transfer line and ion source 
was 250 °C and 200 °C respectively. Helium (99.999%) was 
used as the carrier gas, the flow control mode was constant 
pressure, and the set pressure was 100 kPa. The analyses 
were performed in the full scan mode, monitoring the mass 
range of the detector was set to m/z 50–650.
Qualitative Identification of Metabolites
Preliminary identification of compounds was performed 
firstly on NIST 11 library; the qualitative standard of the 
database was that the similarity was greater than 80%. Then, 
the compounds were further qualitatively identified by ana-
lytical standards.
Raw Data Preprocessing
Divided the peak area of the compound by the peak area 
of heptadecanoic acid for standardization correction, then 
amplified the value by one hundred times, and performed 
logarithmic conversion to achieve normal distribution. After 
that, the corrected peak areas of all identified metabolites 
were used for further analysis.
Statistical Analysis
Data were presented as mean ± standard deviation (SD). 
SIMCA-P software (Version 14.0, Umetrices, Umea, 
