injection, followed by one injection of quality control. We 
integrated the data of 13 quality controls, 62 patients with 
PD and 60 healthy people, then imported them into SIMCA-
P software for modeling, and chose the principal compo-
nent analysis model (PCA). PCA is an unsupervised model, 
which belongs to exploratory analysis, and can generally 
reflect the total metabolic differences between samples in 
each group and the variance between samples in each group. 
As shown in Fig. 2, QC samples are clustered closely, which 
indicates that the difference between samples in the group is 
small, indicating that the analysis method is stable. Moreo-
ver, there are obvious cluster differences between PD and 
health, indicating that there are differences in metabolic pat-
terns between the two groups.
Data‑Driven Prediction of PD
Due to the complexity of metabolomics data, unsupervised 
analysis model PCA could not distinguish samples well with 
insufficient differences between groups. In order to make PD 
and health show a better separation trend, orthogonal partial 
least squares discriminant analysis model (OPLS-DA) was 
used to carry out multivariate statistical analysis on health 
and PD in the train set. OPLS-DA can filter out noises 
unrelated to classification information and improve the 
analytical ability and effectiveness of the model. As shown 
in Fig. 3A, OPLS-DA score plot can distinguish health 
from PD well. However, there may be a risk of over-fitting 
in this model. In this study, 20 permutations were used 
to verify the model internally. If the intercept of R2 in Y 
axis is less than 0.4 and the intercept of Q2 in Y axis is less 
than 0.05, it can be considered that the model has not been 
over-fitted. As shown in Fig. 3B, the model was successfully 
modeled and there was no over-fitting. Then, the Variable 
Importance in Projection (VIP) value was used to screen 
meaningful differential metabolites. VIP value is an index 
to summarize the importance of each variable in driving 
the observed population separation. VIP > 1 means that the 
contribution of this variable to the model is greater than the 
average value. At the same time, the screened differential 
metabolites should be tested by independent sample t test 
and the results should have statistical differences, that is, 
p < 0.05. The global expression of the screened differential 
metabolites in individuals in the group can be visually 
presented by heat map, and the redder the color, the higher 
the relative content. Heat map is a visualization display 
of difference data and can cluster samples. As shown in 
Fig. 3D, between health and PD, the expression of acetic 
acid in the PD increased, while the expression of propanoic 
acid and 2,3,4-trihydroxybutyric acid in the PD group 
decreased, and the expression distribution of differential 
metabolites showed obvious clustering.
Selection of Significant Features Which Diagnose PD
In order to confirm the accuracy of the differential metabo-
lites screened in the train set, we analyzed the expression of 
these three metabolites between health and PD in the valida-
tion set (Fig. 4), and the results showed that the change trend 
of differential metabolites was consistent with that of the 
training set. Meanwhile, the receiver operator characteristic 
curve (ROC) was used to evaluate the diagnostic potential of 
the differential metabolites (Fig. 5). Using “Youden index” 
to determine the best cut-off value, and get the specificity 
and sensitivity of the metabolites in the diagnosis of disease 
the results showed that the area under the curve of acetic 
acid and propanoic acid is as high as 0.981, while the diag-
nostic specificity of propanoic acid is 94.4%, and the sensi-
tivity is 100% (Table 3), which indicates that propanoic acid 
is the most potential diagnostic marker.
We also analyzed the expression differences of acetic 
acid, propanoic acid, and 2,3,4-trihydroxybutyric acid in 
the early and late stages of PD, medicated PD, and drug 
naïve PD. Compared with ESPD, acetic acid increased sig-
nificantly in ASPD, while propanoic acid and 2,3,4-trihy-
droxybutyric acid tended to be lower in ASPD (Fig. 6A), 
but the difference was not statistically significant. Between 
medicated PD and drug naive PD, we found that propanoic 
acid increased significantly in medicated PD, and there was 
no obvious change in acetic acid and 2,3,4-trihydroxybutyric 
acid (Fig. 6B). All these findings indicated that acetic acid 
and propanoic acid may play key roles in the occurrence and 
development of PD.
