Intestinal microbiota can metabolize pyruvic acid to pro-
duce acetic acid through acetyl-CoA or Wood-Ljungdahl 
pathway, and convert succinic acid to methyl malonyl-CoA 
to produce propanoic acid through succinic acid pathway 
(Fig. 8B).The abnormal contents of acetic acid and propi-
onic acid in Parkinson’s patients were observed in this study, 
which may be related to the intestinal microbiome disorder 
in Parkinson’s patients. Short-chain fatty acids are important 
metabolites of intestinal microorganisms, and participate in 
different biological processes of hosts as signal molecules 
[22, 23]. Abnormal metabolism of short-chain fatty acids 
may indicate that the homeostasis is destroyed.
Discussion
This study presented a comprehensive metabolic evalu-
ation for PD by GC–MS. The preliminary qualitative 
metabolites included short-chain fatty acids (i.e., propa-
noic acid, butanoic acid, and pentanoic acid), long-chain 
fatty acids (i.e., tetradecanoic acid, palmitelaidic acid, 
and oleic acid), amino acids (i.e., leucine, isoleucine, and 
tryptophan), and carbohydrates (i.e., ribitol, galactose, and 
fructose). Among them, we found that the concentration 
of propanoic acid and 2,3,4-trihydroxybutyric acid were 
