lower in PD than in healthy controls, and acetic acid con-
centration was significantly higher in PD. There is con-
siderable controversy about the content change of acetic 
acid and propanoic acid in PD. Shin C et al. reported that 
increased acetic acid was related to PD, but no difference 
in propanoic acid was observed [24], and only after the 
covariates were corrected can the statistical significance 
of acetic acid content change between PD and health be 
observed. However, another research did not observe the 
difference of acetic acid between PD and health but found 
that propanoic acid increased in PD [25]. One recent study 
found that compared with healthy controls, the plasma 
acetic acid level of PD patients was lower and propanoic 
acid level was higher [26]. Currently, the diagnosis of PD 
is made through clinical diagnosis, without exact clinical 
markers and imaging data. The research results of plasma 
metabolomics of the disease are likely to be affected by 
the lax inclusion standard. Also, the difference of research 
results may also be related to analysis methods, instru-
ment status, sample storage and treatment, and analysts. 
For ensuring the accuracy of biological sample analysis 
to the greatest extent, researchers should do a good job 
in methodology investigation, make the instrument in the 
best working condition, and ensure that analysts are rela-
tively stable in an analysis project.
In our research, we found higher level of acetic acid and 
lower level of propanoic acid and 2,3,4-trihydroxybutyric 
acid in PD than in health. Besides, we also observed that 
acetic acid increased in ASPD than ESPD, and propanoic 
acid was significantly higher in medicated PD than in drug 
naïve PD. Our results were not completely consistent with 
the studies mentioned above; this may be related to different 
inclusion criteria for patients. When the difference of acetic 
acid and propanoic acid was observed in PD and health, 
ROC was further used to evaluate their diagnostic ability for 
PD. The results showed that acetic acid and propanoic acid 
were able to obtain correct diagnostic value of PD with high 
sensitivity and specificity, and the area under curve of them 
were both reached 0.981, suggesting that they were available 
in diagnosis of PD.
Mounting evidence shows that PD is not only a brain 
disease but also a digestive disorder [27, 28]. Gastrointes-
tinal symptoms occur in almost every patient with PD at 
some point, which is a frequent and early event in the course 
of PD, and gastrointestinal involvement may be critically 
involved in the early development of the disease [29]. Gut 
