1 3
microbiota could be an environmental modulator of the 
pathogenesis of PD and intestinal inflammation has been 
suggested to play a role in development of PD [30, 31]. A 
study assumed that short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs) concen-
tration in the peripheral venous blood was related to gut 
dysbiosis, compromised intestinal barrier induced by inflam-
mation may contribute to the “leak” and persistence of gut-
produced SCFAs into the systemic circulation in infectious 
and autoinflammatory diseases [32]. SCFAs are primarily 
produced in the large intestine by gut microbiota fermenta-
tion of plant-derived carbohydrates, and as signal molecules, 
they affect a series of activities of the host [33]. Acetic acid 
and propanoic acid are the most abundant SCFAs in gastro-
intestinal tract. A research found that acetic acid is produced 
by most of the enteric bacteria such as Lactobacillus and 
Bifidobacterium, and propanoic acid is produced by Phasco-
larctobacterium succinatutens [34]. Some studies indicated 
that acetic acid–producing microbiota were increased in PD 
that could result in increased levels of plasma acetic acid 
[35, 36]. SCFAs not only act on intestine, but also can act 
on distal parts such as the brain, and regulate autonomic 
nerve function independently of central nervous system [37, 
38]. The concentration of SCFAs varies along the length 
of the gut, with highest levels in the cecum and proximal 
colon, while it declines toward the distal colon, SCFAs 
can be transported to the peripheral circulation through the 
portal vein and act on the liver and peripheral tissues [39]. 
Propionic acid is metabolized in the liver, and its concen-
tration in the peripheral blood is low. Acetate is the most 
abundant SCFAs in the peripheral circulation [39]. SCFAs 
can directly stimulate the motility and secretion of intesti-
nal tract, activate the immunosuppressive mechanism, and 
keep intestinal homeostasis [40, 41]. Our research found the 
dysregulation of short-chain fatty acid metabolism in PD, 
and these abnormalities also appeared in the early and late 
stages of PD, suggesting that the gut dysbiosis was related 
to the progress of PD.
Some limitations existed in this study. First, we lacked 
a standard control of 2,3,4-trihydroxybutyric acid, and this 
part of data needs further confirmation. Second, as poten-
tial candidate markers, there is a lack of evidence that these 
markers are unique to PD patients rather than other cen-
tral nervous system diseases. In the following research, 
we should observe the dynamic changes of these potential 
markers in the progress of PD through the follow-up sur-
vey, and collect samples of other central nervous system 
diseases to comprehensively evaluate the analysis results. 
These deficiencies suggested that further research needs to 
be improved.
Conclusion
In conclusion, an untargeted GC–MS analysis of plasma 
from PD reveals abnormal metabolism in SCFAs compared 
to health. Acetic acid and propanoic acid may be a potential 
biomarker for differentiating PD from health. Our results can 
help to establish a panel of biomarkers associated with PD, 
promote the early detection of PD, and further understand 
the development process of the disease.
